 Worshipful Company of Haberdashers, one of the Great Twelve Livery Companies of the City of London.", 'answer': "Haberdashers' Aske's School for Girls"}) (input_keys=None), Example({'augmented': True, 'context': ['Gustave Lussi | Gustave François Lussi (June 2, 1898 – June 23, 1993) was a figure skating coach. His students include many champions, such as Dick Button, Tenley Albright, Maria Jelinek / Otto Jelinek, Donald Jackson, Alena Vrzáňová, Ronald Robertson, Ronald Ludington, Barbara Ann Scott, David Jenkins, Hayes Jenkins, Emmerich Danzer, Dorothy Hamill, John Misha Petkevich, and John Curry.', "Dorothy Hamill | Dorothy Stuart Hamill (born July 26, 1956) is a retired American figure skater. She is the 1976 Olympic champion and 1976 World champion in ladies' singles.", "Françoise Gouny | Françoise Guittet née Françoise Gouny (12 April 1925 – 2009) was a French fencer. She competed in the women's individual foil event at the 1948 Summer Olympics.", 'Samantha Hamill | Samantha Hamill (born 23 February 1991) is an Australian competitive swimmer. She competed in the 200-metre butterfly and the 400-metre individual medley at the 2008 Summer Olympics in Beijing, and the 200-metre butterfly at the 2012 Summer Olympics in London.'], 'question': 'Both Gustave Francoise Lussi and Dorothy Hamill were a part of what Olympic sport?', 'reasoning': 'Gustave Lussi was a figure skating coach and Dorothy Hamill was a figure skater. Figure skating is an Olympic sport.', 'answer': 'Figure skating'}) (input_keys=None), Example({'augmented': True, 'context': ['Ivan Illich | Ivan Illich ( ; 4 September 1926 – 2 December 2002) was a Croatian-Austrian philosopher, Roman Catholic priest, and critic of the institutions of modern Western culture, who addressed contemporary practices in education, medicine, work, energy use, transportation, and economic development.', 'Ivan Stojanović | Ivan Stojanović (1829–1900) was a Serbian Catholic priest who wrote the book "Dubrovačka Književnost", published in 1900, arguing that the people of Dubrovnik were Roman Catholic by religion, but by language Serbs. He was involved with the literary journal "Slovinac".', "Ivan Šarić (archbishop) | Ivan Šarić (27 September 1871 – 16 July 1960) was a Roman Catholic priest who became the archbishop of the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Vrhbosna (Sarajevo) in 1922. In 1940 Šarić was tasked by the national bishops' conference to put together the first modern Croatian translation of the Bible. A benefactor of the Bosnian Croat population, Šarić became a controversial figure because of his pro-Ustaše activities and rhetoric, including his support for forcible conversions to Catholicism inside the Independent State of Croatia during World War II.", 'Ivan Margitych | Ivan Margitych (Ukrainian: Іван Маргітич ; 4 February 1921 – 7 September 2003) was a Ruthenian Greek Catholic hierarch. He was an auxiliary bishop of the Ruthenian Catholic Eparchy of Mukacheve from 1987 to 2002 and titular bishop of Scopelus in Haemimonto from 1991 to 2003.', 'Ivan Rafael Rodić | Ivan Rafael Rodić (also Ivo Rodić , Italian: "Giovanni Raffaele Rodic" ) (June 15, 1870 – May 10, 1954), was a Croatian Franciscan priest who served as the first Archbishop of the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Belgrade-Smederevo between 1924 and 1936.'], 'question': 'The Centro Intercultural de Documentacion was fonded by a Croatian-Austrian philosopher who also held what title in the Roman Catholic church?', 'reasoning': 'The Centro Intercultural de Documentacion (CIDOC) was founded by Ivan Illich, a Croatian-Austrian philosopher. Ivan Illich was also a Roman Catholic priest. The question asks for the title he held in the Roman Catholic church, which is "priest".', 'answer': 'priest'}) (input_keys=None)]

